Should I separate the generalization of the liminf / limsup lemmas from the other small ENNReal lemmas? The original PR was around 50 lines diff, but the requested generalization of the liminf lemma ended up relying on PR #14591 to generalize liminf/limsup lemmas to assume only coboundedness in one direction plus still ENNReal specific adaptations which alone are many times the size of the original simple PR.

(I obviously think it is absolutely the right thing to do to fix the generality of the ENNReal liminf lemma as well as to fix the generality of liminf and limsup lemmas in all conditionally complete linear orders with order topology, so thanks S√©bastien for the careful and useful review comment!)
Yeah, it looks like you already split most of this off. Can you remove the bits of this now present in the other PR?

This PR/issue depends on:
* ~~leanprover-community/mathlib4#14591~~

bors d+

Assuming the `norm_cast` suggestion works and you implement the other suggestions:

bors d+

Isn't it enough to assume the weaker condition that `xs i` is eventually not equal to ` ‚àû`? If the liminf is infinity in this case, it means that the sequence is tending to infinity, so the liminf in NNReal is probably zero (what other choice of junk value could we have? I haven't checked).

True. The existing lemma `Monotone.map_liminf_of_continuousAt` used here had suboptimal assumptions, so it looks like the right course is to generalize that first. I made PR #14591 for the generalization. With it, I will return and generalize this lemma (and `liminf_toReal_eq` above, which inherited a similar suboptimal assumption).

Actually, I belatedly realized that your observation was stronger than the general generalization it made me think of. In the ENNReal case the junk value choice should allow for an even weaker assumption than coboundedness. I will therefore think about fixing the ENNReal-lemmas independently of the generalization in the other PR, which I nevertheless still think is fixing suboptimal generality elsewhere. [UPDATE: The requested generalization ended up depending on the other PR's generalization in any case.]

I moved the generalization of this lemma and the ones below to #15115. (Unfortunately I missed that these are not completely independent: the new PR still depends on one lemma in the current simple PR. I still think the division makes the PRs clearer that way.)
Same comment here.
Why do you need the rfl here? Missing lemmas?

The goal after this `simp only [...]`, before `rfl`, was essentially the following lemma, which is true `by rfl`  but indeed seemed to be missing. However, creating it and making it a `@[simp]` lemma causes a loop in a simp later, so maybe there is a reason... On the other hand, the RHS below should definitely in my opinion be the simp normal form of this expression!

```
theorem coe_toNNReal_eq_toReal (z : ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû) : (z.toNNReal : ‚Ñù) = z.toReal := rfl
```

I added it now without `@[simp]` tag, and providing this to `simp` now avoids the last `rfl`.
Could you please make it a `simp` lemma?

Sorry, do you mean making `ENNReal.tendsto_pow_atTop_nhds_top` a `simp` lemma? I could do that, but I thought would be unlikely that users are ever in exactly a position where this lemma could fire in a `simp` call.
Oh, do you mean making it an "iff" statement with `1<r` as the RHS simp normal form? That makes sense! Thanks!
This seems to be true for `c = ‚àû`: both sides are equal to `‚àû`.
Indeed, thanks! I will try to drop the hypothesis.

unless the attributes aren't declared yet, I think this works:
```suggestion
instance : MeasurableSMul‚ÇÇ ‚Ñù‚â•0 ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû where
  measurable_smul := show Measurable fun r : ‚Ñù‚â•0 √ó ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû ‚Ü¶ (r.1 : ‚Ñù‚â•0) * r.2 by fun_prop
```

style
```suggestion
protected theorem zpow_neg {x : ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû} (x_ne_zero : x ‚â† 0) (x_ne_top : x ‚â† ‚ä§) (m : ‚Ñ§) :
    x ^ (-m) = (x ^ m)‚Åª¬π :=
```

arguably, because Lean doesn't need them for parsing, we should drop the parens around `x ^ m` too, but I like keeping them for readability.
```suggestion
protected theorem zpow_sub {x : ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû} (x_ne_zero : x ‚â† 0) (x_ne_top : x ‚â† ‚ä§) (m n : ‚Ñ§) :
    x ^ (m - n) = (x ^ m) * (x ^ n)‚Åª¬π := by
```
Probably you want to tag this `@[norm_cast]`, not `@[simp]`.
Thanks! I was not (actively) aware of `@[norm_cast]` tag, but it definitely seems appropriate. I will try and see the consequences (especially no loops).
